{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39f73eac-0721-49de-969f-4d2013803f74","content":"\n\nRun **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update, since your workload packages may now be incompatible.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or partially-installed workloads but won't pull newer versions to match a new SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, try `dotnet workload restore` from your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project's `global.json` or targets.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65bb9f6b-5f32-4859-afbf-75091ae65556","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":244},"id":"56e77a26-837b-4e44-9da1-04fd7e8f1a61","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:51:34.906Z","parentId":"806eefd5-93d2-4596-b2d4-937c11b7d6ec"}
